The <b>Maui Alauahio</b> or <b>Maui <span class="unicode">ʻ</span>Alauahio</b> (<i>Paroreomyza montana</i>), also known as the <b>Maui Nui <span class="unicode">ʻ</span>Alauahio</b> or <b>Maui Creeper</b>, is a species of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Finch" title="Finch">finch</a> in the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hawaiian_honeycreeper" title="Hawaiian honeycreeper">Hawaiian honeycreeper</a> <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Family_(biology)" title="Family (biology)">subfamily</a>, Drepanidinae. It is <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Endemism" title="Endemism">endemic</a> to <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hawaii" title="Hawaii">Hawaii</a>. The name, <b>Maui <span class="unicode">ʻ</span>Alauahio</b>, is somewhat misleading because the species seems to have occurred on most, if not all, parts of the ancient <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maui_Nui" title="Maui Nui">Maui Nui</a>. Its natural <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Habitat" title="Habitat">habitats</a> are <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hawaiian_tropical_dry_forests" title="Hawaiian tropical dry forests">dry</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hawaiian_tropical_rainforests#Mixed_mesic_forests" title="Hawaiian tropical rainforests">mesic</a> and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hawaiian_tropical_rainforests#Wet_forests" title="Hawaiian tropical rainforests">wet forests</a>, as well as <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hawaiian_tropical_high_shrublands" title="Hawaiian tropical high shrublands">high</a> and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hawaiian_tropical_low_shrublands" title="Hawaiian tropical low shrublands">low shrublands</a> and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plantation" title="Plantation">plantations</a>. It is threatened by <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Habitat_loss" title="Habitat loss" class="mw-redirect">habitat loss</a>.
